    12 /**
    13 * Class which represent a constraint. Provides attributes and methods for details of the constraint.
    14 *
    15 * #### Notes for Through Constraints <span id="notes"></span>
    16 * Through constraints are used for many to many relationships. Actually there isn't such a thing called
    17 * **many to many relationship** or **through constraint** in the database engine. They are concepts to describe
    18 * records which may be related more than one record on both sides. For example an invoice may contain more than product and
    19 * a product may related to more than one invoice. Those relationships are solved a so called many to many **join table**.
    20 *
    21 * Constraint class supports many to many relationships. Since those constraints are not present in database engine,
    22 * they are extracted by estimation/interpretation. Many non-join tables in a database could have more than one
    23 * foreign key constraints, and they may not meant to be join tables, but they have still through relationships .
    24 *
    25 * <span id="exampleSchema"></span>Below is a database schema as an example:
    26 * ```
    27 * size -------------------
    28 * id (PK) | ---------------------------< line_item >------------ cart
    29 * name | | product_id (PFK) id (PK)
    30 * | | cart_id (PFK) name
    31 * ^ |
    32 * color -------------< product >------------- vendor
    33 * id (PK) id (PK) id (PK)
    34 * name name name
    35 * color_id (FK)
    36 * size_id (FK)
    37 * vendor_id (FK)
    38 * ```
    39 * Below is the same schema as image:
    40 * ![Database Schema](../../images/schema-through.png)
    41 *
    42 * Product table has 3 foreign key constraints. It is obvious that product table is not meant to be a many to many join table.
    43 * However product could have been join table for `size & vendor`, `color & vendor` and `size & color`. As a result size,
    44 * color and vendor tables would have many to many `through constraints`.
    45 *
    46 */

    11 /**
    12 * @description
    13 * Class which represent a many to many relationship which resembles `belongsToMany` or `hasManyThrough` relations in ORMs (Object Relational Mappers).
    14 * Provides attributes and methods for details of the relationship.
    15 *
    16 * Actually there isn't such a thing called **many to many relationship** or **through constraint** in the database engine.
    17 * They are concepts to describe records which may be related more than one record on both sides.
    18 * For example an invoice may contain more than product and a product may related to more than one invoice.
    19 * Those relationships are solved a so called many to many **join table**.
    20 *
    21 * Since those relations are not present in database engine, they are extracted by estimation/interpretation.
    22 * Many non-join tables in a database could have more than one foreign key constraints,
    23 * and they may not meant to be join tables, but they still appear to have through relationships.
    24 *
    25 * <span id="exampleSchema"></span>Below is a database schema as an example:
    26 * ```
    27 * size -------------------
    28 * id (PK) | ---------------------------< line_item >------------ cart
    29 * name | | product_id (PFK) id (PK)
    30 * | | cart_id (PFK) name
    31 * ^ |
    32 * color -------------< product >------------- vendor
    33 * id (PK) id (PK) id (PK)
    34 * name name name
    35 * color_id (FK)
    36 * size_id (FK)
    37 * vendor_id (FK)
    38 *
    39 * ```
    40 * Below is the same schema as image:
    41 * ![Database Schema](../../images/schema-through.png)
    42 *
    43 * Some definitions used in descriptions for {@link M2MRelation}.
    44 * * ** Source Table: ** Table which this relationship belongs to.
    45 * * ** Join Table: ** Table that contains common fields from two or more other tables.
    46 * * ** Target Table: ** Table that is related to base table through a join table.
    47 * <br><br>
    48 * Product table has 3 foreign key constraints. Product table is not meant to be a many to many join table.
    49 * However product could have been join table for `size & vendor`, `color & vendor` and `size & color`. As a result size,
    50 * color and vendor tables would have many to many relationships.
    51 * @example
    52 * // Example tables have single primary key and and examples first relation. So zero index ([0]) is used. Use all array elements if necessary.
    53 * // product ----< line_item >---- cart
    54 * // (source) (join) (target)
    55 *
    56 * let relation = product.m2mRelations[0]; // RELATION: product ---< line_item >--- cart
